messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

Before we go, here's an option: invert the type and name for Q_APPLICATION_STATIC.

Then you could write:

 Q_APPLICATION_STATIC(name, Type{foo, bar})

and that would work. It's too late for Q_GLOBAL_STATIC and if we did this, we'd have inconsistent API. But thoughts?

Patch Set 1:

>  Q_APPLICATION_STATIC(name, Type{foo, bar})

Works for me.

Patch Set 1:

really? such inconsistency *will* bite users from time to time - for no particularly good reason, given that an alternative proposal is on the table.

Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

I see this change also includes a new class and extending the platform detection. I think we should be very careful in the handling of browsers and platforms, as this is doomed to become a nightmare of combinatorics if we don't plan this carefully. I believe a better approach is to rather program assuming we're given a set of capabilities and limitations, which optimally should be determined in a platform agnostic way. Of course, in the real world we have to account for the fact that X platform requires Y behavior, but let's define platform/browser capability in one place and base the rest of the codebase around that.

Patch Set 4:

> (2 comments)

I think we should be very careful in the handling of browsers and platforms, as this is doomed to become a nightmare of combinatorics if we don't plan this carefully. I believe a better approach is to rather program assuming we're given a set of capabilities and limitations, which optimally should be determined in a platform agnostic way. Of course, in the real world we have to account for the fact that X platform requires Y behavior, but let's define platform/browser capability in one place and base the rest of the codebase around that.


These platforms act entirely different in this situation. There is no other way to grab Android's virtual key input, and it is not needed on the others and seemed to stop iOS v keyboard from popping up. Windows has a different way to popup the virtual keyboard altogether.

Patch Set 4:

Also, see https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/385490 and consider how QWasmCompositor and QWasmInputContext should relate and interact.

Patch Set 4:

Looks like there's a VirtualKeyboard API now: https://web.dev/virtualkeyboard/

Should be worth investigating. It's supported on the Chromium derivatives, but not on Safari. See https://caniuse.com/?search=VirtualKeyboard .
